\\n        }\\n    }\\n\\n    private static Object getMemberValue(Method member, Annotation instance) {\\n        Object value = invoke(member, instance);\\n        if (value == null) {\\n            throw new IllegalArgumentException(\\\"Annotation member value \\\" + instance.getClass().getName() + \\\".\\\"\\n                    + member.getName() + \\\" must not be null\\\");\\n        }\\n        return value;\\n    }\\n\\n    private static Object invoke(Method method, Object instance) {\\n        try {\\n            if (!method.isAccessible())\\n                SecurityActions.setAccessible(method);\\n            return method.invoke(instance);\\n        } catch (IllegalArgumentException | IllegalAccessException | InvocationTargetException e) {\\n            throw new RuntimeException(\\\"Error checking value of member method \\\" + method.getName() + \\\" on \\\"\\n                    + method.getDeclaringClass(), e);\\n        }\\n    }\\n\\n}\\n\"}], \"isError\": false, \"timestamp\": 1780888702037}}\n989:[recv] {\"type\": \"turn_end\", \"message\": {\"role\": \"assistant\", \"content\": [{\"type\": \"thinking\", \"thinking\": \"**Evaluating Java security manager changes**\\n\\nI'm thinking about the recent changes in Java regarding the security manager. In Java 24, using `System.getSecurityManager()` might return null, which complicates coverage. There seems to be a need to adjust the tests to be version-agnostic while still accounting for native calls. With Java 25, methods related to the security manager are deprecated, and it’s unclear how to handle coverage under these new circumstances. I’m considering modifying the build conditions to accommodate these differences and improve our test coverage accordingly.\\n\\n**Considering test configurations for Java**\\n\\nI'm exploring if I can run tests under native support for the security manager, but there are challenges with coverage in Java 25. Using a public API for triggering privileged actions isn't an option anymore. The current build ensures JDK 21 starts with the default security manager, but later tests may remove it. I need to analyze the coverage report to understand why Java 25 didn’t pass. There might be ways to adjust the Gradle settings, but launching with specific properties on Java 25 might lead to failures.\\n\\n**Reasoning about JDK 24 security manager**\\n\\nI’m thinking about the changes in JDK 24, specifically how JEP 486 has permanently disabled the security manager. Setting `java.security.manager` to allow seems to be ignored in the documentation. It looks like calling `System::setSecurityManager` always throws an UnsupportedOperationException, and `System::getSecurityManager` returns null, so the policy won't apply. If I use the command-line option `-Djava.security.manager`, it might result in an error if set to anything other than allow. I need to clarify these points.\", \"thinkingSignature\": \"{\\\"id\\\":\\\"rs_0a276e9d282643a6016a263470582081949f5b3050818d616a\\\",\\\"type\\\":\\\"reasoning\\\",\\\"content\\\":[],\\\"encrypted_content\\\":\\\"gAAAAABqJjR9jnGPGHREjB_NiadXNTc8u7Tvvsvhuw-Txgwk-NZX5fcYvq0Fqu24nSw0W0fI82B3usMUUiB9zISWXNoOh1mX5EIGLkJIl2fr-l1WetqwbTO7IL8g5bwiqD3ioKzX3VzN3oLB9Bx_GFjIh5qMllwgarWL3ZeEppOhwR5TB8K1q45_UYQBue6bbe_dXO7JFvbjFbn_PE4xr3-dByysWiFLU-DO-h-o83MTdrIBt1xfsudZNXR-ojYb9vPBKQFE38x__67Q-D5tuwjR1RF7X0yxp_AeUuQg4X42oZ8drDLMohvsp8ceHWH6iXnZkoskSZb9RVGKN-hUMsGcuOoni_T2Gc9TOoC4AEibpNiHNQ83iV6VQXjFfGk5DKECixCH5BSCopptGcYc2158702RxMKE0fQCRDUUcf0yN2XZ6ZuEqcn-6ebJGxqJi0frZd-dMmk9ZB8RCoUNAKdjvBOPFawM7LVmt28UGbqtSkTrJPI0QStx5ZzHNtqG60fTlLftLoWMYFfSZ8XSjLkzXZx9fdM-Ei1Zkt8LfO95VDnpRgds5GNxGlQiUSJo9KEFnTmB5Tn2uzujRzgdtM7GH5H0x7IldH3q93PSq4cNDBgblDz_BdFAjDTu-Ho9iK4xz1dNLn8WQCFRlkJlPDMUf5DfAiI7b-8pyRKwFoGdCvRubd4FxrtPYxLAafcdlSy63lXoEgv29n-VmSkaSAO9lwCtw6JkRgYw6eKFj92J6xhylXS755-eMvww2NCc8lrnHjL0hH6Hq9ZRZkR24iGbkKjhYiiYVYgtw0rWe1efctw1T1h-07WN6zUc1vev6i16YWfCkIMJYQUkVK4xAVRnYIn015keekqWV8k5vLBz4Q4Y92RqCWX67_fGgBGcOwOQXdBzKtLyXhV